The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, February 27, 2004 				 US biotech firms base in Andhra
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, Feb. 26: Sigma-Aldrich, a leader in biotechnology with $1.2 billion in annual sales, is setting up a research base in Hyderabad. The company headquartered, in St Louis, Missouri, is acquiring a 15-acre space in the ICICI Knowledge Park in Hyderabad that houses around 30 similar laboratories, said . Vaghul, chairman of ICICI Bank.																								Sigma-Aldrich is seeking a lease agreement for 99 years, but ICICI Knowledge Park is not entitled to lease out space in the Park for more than 30 years, without approval of the government of Andhra Pradesh, Vaghul said. The company will invest of $8 million (Rs 36 crore) to set up a 50,000 sq ft laboratory-cum-production facility in partnership with the AP government, reports PTI from Hyderabad.																								Jai Nagarkatti, president (scientific research) of Sigma-Aldrich, said the laboratory would start operating in the first quarter of 2005. It will serve as a feeder site for the companys production facilities in Germany, Switzerland, UK and the US.																								Sigma-Aldrich has operations in 34 countries, excluding India, and employs over 6,000 people. It has developed and manufactures over 40,000 products. It is perhaps the biggest biotechnology firm to set up operations in India.Interest rate																								Addressing the Indian Chamber of Commerce, Vaghul cautioned interest rates were going to harden  though not in the near future  and the feel good factors would peter out.																								Interest rates were soft because of the liquidity overhang, and share prices were rising as overseas funds flowed into the country.																								But a reversal is inevitable. There are signs that Japan and the US are coming out of recession. Europe hasnt yet  probably wouldnt for yet another year  but it too would, Vaghul said. 
